    <text id="R155499T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Confederate Major Michael Harman discusses recommendations for troop movements
                    issued in January, 1862, just before he left Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Gen. W. W. LORING,<lb/> Cmdg. Army of the Northwest:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1862-01-04">January 4, 1862.</date>
                        <name type="place">WINCHESTER, VA.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>GEN.:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I inclose you a letter from Gen. Edward Johnson, which I received just as I was
                    leaving Staunton. I immediately telegraphed Gen. Cooper, advising that two
                    regiments be sent up to re-enforce him, if it was possible to do so, as the
                    enemy might get to his rear by the Huntersville road and cut off his supplies. I
                    write by this express to Gen. Jackson, inclosing a copy of Gen. Johnson's
                    letter, thinking you might not be near him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am, very respectfully, your obedient servant,</salute>
                    <signed>M. G. HARMAN,<lb/> Lieut.-Col., &amp;c.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
